properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.location: Lake Fyans, Pomonal, Bellfield, Halls Gap
properties.webBody:
This is an updated Watch and Act message issued for Bellfield, Halls Gap, Lake Fyans and Pomonal. 

Community Meetings will be held today:
  • Pomonal Community Hall at 3:00pm.
  • Ararat Relief Centre, Alexander Oval, Waratah Ave at 4:30pm.
  • Stawell Relief Centre, Grampians Community Health, 8-22 Patrick Street at 5:45pm.
  • Dadswells Bridge at 7:30pm. 
Click here to view the Community Newsletter for the Bellfield Fire.

The following information is unchanged. 

  • There is a bushfire at Grampians National Park, Bellfield that is not yet under control. 
  • Firefighters have been able to slow the spread of fire for now, but the situation can change at any time. You must monitor conditions and be ready to act.
If conditions worsen, don't wait, leaving now is the safest option - conditions may change and get worse very quickly. Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 
What you should do: 
  • Monitor changes to the situation. Increased wind speed, change in wind direction, smoke or poor visibility can indicate the situation is changing.
  • Protect yourself and your family. 
  • If you are away from home, do not return.

If the situation changes or you feel unsafe you should leave:
  • Take your pets, medications, mobile phone and charger.
  • Many people have died trying to leave at the last minute during fires. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends that are away from the warning area or Ararat or Stawell.
  • Emergency Relief Centres are located at Alexander Oval Community Centre on Waratah Ave, Ararat and Grampians Community Health 8-22 Patrick Street, Stawell. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • Road Closures 
Ararat-Halls Gap Road (C222) from Moyston-Dunkeld Road, Moyston to Grampians Road, Halls Gap
Black Range Road (C221) from Pickering Road, Stawell to Pomonal East Road, Pomonal. 

  • For the most up to date information 
Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/) or call 13 11 70 for road closures.
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 15/02/2024 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Community Information
properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for water quality at Lake Bolac. 
  • High levels of blue-green algae have been detected in the lake. 
  • The algal bloom is expected to remain until there is significant rainfall to flush the lake or cooler conditions slow the algae. 
  • Regular testing is being conducted to identify new outbreaks or changes that might indicate improved water quality. 
  • This notification will be reviewed weekly and updated as the situation changes.
Warning signs have been installed at the lake.

You should avoid direct contact with affected water in Lake Bolac.

Do not swim in affected areas or use water for cooking, drinking, washing or showering. Boiling the water will not make it safe. 
What you should do:
  • Visit Parks Victoria website (https://www.parks.vic.gov.au/places-to-see/parks/lake-bolac-highway-park) for more information. 
  • Observe information signs posted at the lake.
Protect your health:
  • Direct contact with water affected by blue green algae can cause skin irritation, sore eyes, ears and nose. If swallowed it can cause cramps, nausea and vomiting. 
  • If you do come into contact with affected water, wash your skin immediately in clean cool water. 
  • Boiling affected water does not make it safe to drink. Boiling water bursts the blue green algae cells and releases toxins into the water making it more likely that you will experience symptoms. 
  • If you are experiencing any health issues after contact with affected water seek medical advice from your local doctor or Nurse-On-Call on 1300 60 60 24.
Protect your pets:
  • Pet owners should prevent pets from drinking or having direct contact with contaminated water. 
Agriculture information: 
  • Irrigation water contaminated with blue-green algae should not be spray irrigated on vegetables and fruit, or come in contact with plants being grown for food during processing and packing. 
  • Fruit and vegetables grown in the affected areas are safe to consume if farmers follow recommendations regarding blue-green algae
Impacts in your area:
  • The water is  green as a result of the algae bloom.
Boating and fishing:
  • Boating and fishing is still allowed in these areas, however care needs to be taken.
  • Fish caught from affected areas should be rinsed and cleaned thoroughly in fresh water, and internal organs removed from the fish and discarded before eating. 
  • Do not eat mussels, crayfish or yabbies caught from the affected area. 
This message was issued by Department of Energy, Environment and Climate Action.

The next update is expected by 31/03/2024 05:20 pm or as the situation changes.

Information about blue green algae:
  • For information on blue green algae visit: www2.health.vic.gov.au/public-health/water/blue-green-algae-cyanobac teria.
Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter.
  • Tune into ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Advice is being issued for Areas North of Grampians including Stawell, Horsham, Dimboola and Murtoa.
  • Smoke from Fires in the Grampians National Park may be experienced in the area.
  • Due to weather conditions, smoke is expected to linger overnight. 
  • The smoke may aggravate existing heart and lung conditions and cause irritated eyes, coughing and wheezing.
Smoke can affect people's health. You should be aware of the health impacts of smoke on you and others.
What you should do:

  • Your nose is an excellent smoke detector. If you can smell smoke, take the necessary precautions to protect your health. You can self-assess the air quality near you using: https://www.epa.vic.gov.au/for-community/environmental-information/air-quality/smoke/smoke-your-health.
Take action to reduce your exposure to smoke and protect your health: 
  • People more sensitive to smoke are those with a heart or lung condition, including asthma; people over the age of 65 years; infants and children; and pregnant women. 
  • If you are sensitive to smoke, limit prolonged or heavy physical activity. Where possible, try to stay indoors. 
  • If you have a heart or lung conditions, take your medication as prescribed by your doctor. 
  • If you are asthmatic, follow your asthma plan and carry reliever medication with you. 
  • For more information on smoke and your health, visit the Better Health Channel. If you are concerned about symptoms, call Nurse on Call on 1300 606 024 or see your doctor. 
  • If you or anyone in your care has trouble breathing or tightness in the chest, call Triple Zero (000) for an ambulance.
Impacts in your area:

  • It may be smoky or hazy in your area. 
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 15/02/2024 08:00 am or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for Emerald and Cockatoo communities.

  • Community Hubs will re-open tomorrow 10.30am to 6.30pm.
  • Cockatoo Community Hub is located at Cockatoo Community Complex - 79 Pakenham Rd Cockatoo.
  • Emerald Community Hub is located at Worrell Reserve  - Emerald-Monbulk Rd, Emerald.
  • Community Hubs have Shire and Emergency Service representatives to inform and support the community where possible.

  • Mobile and Telephone communications maybe unavailable for the area.
  • In case of an emergency, community members with a smart phone and access to the internet at home can use their phone for emergency calls. Alternatively, community members can access public phone at the following locations :
  • 348 MAIN ST OUTSIDE MEDICAL CENTRE, EMERALD
  • 445 BELGRAVE-GEMBROOK RD , EMERALD
  • 44 MCBRIDE ST , COCKATOO

  • Emergency Services are available to support high priority tree removal to support access and egress to homes and damage to home to support livability. Home owners should consider insurance and other supports for tree removal other to providing access and egress.

  •  To ensure your safety, do not drive or walk over downed power lines. Call your electricity company to report any faults .

  • Traffic conditions are poor with downed trees and no lights. Please drive to conditions.

  • Due to the hazards within the area and ensure your safety, visiting the area should be limited to residents and others who have a specific requirement to be there.
Road and Transport
  • For up to date information on road closures, visit VicRoads Traffic Website.

Generators
  • Never use generators indoors or in enclosed areas, that can be deadly. Generators emit carbon monoxide that you cannot see or smell, and it can very quickly cause carbon monoxide poisoning and asphyxiation.
  • Never plug a generator into a wall socket or switchboard to power a house.
  • For more information how to use generators safely go to the Energy Safe website
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

Unless the situation changes, this will be the last message issued for this incident. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
• This Advice message is for Gippsland residents located in the East Gippsland and Wellington Local Government Areas.
  • Extreme weather including storms, strong winds and lightning has resulted in widespread power and telecommunications outages across the Region, with hundreds of power poles and lines down, and some areas facing extended power outages with significant damage to the networks.
  • Bairnsdale and Lake Entrance were significantly impacted including roads, infrastructure, communications and properties.
  • Many local and major roads were impacted by trees and damage. Crews from Local Government and the Department of Transport and Planning are working to open roads as soon as practical.
  • SES, CFA and FFMVic crews have been making steady progress today, clearing roads and removing debris.
  • A number of schools in the area are closed.  A full list of school closures can be found here.
  • All agencies are working closely together to share information and plans to ensure that communities can return to normal functionality as soon as possible.
  • Unnecessary travel into affected areas should be limited due to potential safety concerns including fallen trees and power lines.
Stay informed and be aware of potential hazards caused by the severe weather. Hazards include damaged buildings, trees down debris and fallen power lines.
What you should do: 

  • Park your car undercover and away from trees.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so.
  • Be aware of hazardous trees - heat, fire or recent storms may make trees unstable and more likely to fall during a storm.
  • Stay safe by avoiding dangerous hazards such as fallen trees and fallen powerlines - always assume they are live.
  • If your property has been damaged, have all utilities checked and tested by a licensed technician before you use them.

If you are driving: 
  • Drive slowly and obey all road signs.  If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater.
  • Be aware of road hazards such as mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • For road closure information, check the VicTraffic website (https://traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/), contact your local council or call VicRoads (13 11 70).
Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 

For severe weather related emergency assistance from the SES, phone 132 500.

This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

This will be the final message issued for this incident. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicstorms) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Advice message is being issued for Boweya, Killawarra, Mount Bruno, Wangandary.

  • There is a bushfire at Link Track, Warby Ranges  that is not yet under control.
  • The bushfire is travelling in a north-easterly direction.
There is currently no threat to communities, but you should continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do: 
  • Monitor weather conditions and warnings. 
  • Review your fire survival plan. 
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes.

properties.name: Community Information
properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for Monash, Knox and Greater Dandenong ares
  • Emergency Services are currently responding to high priority incidents to support access and egress to homes and damage to homes to support livability. Home owners should consider insurance and other supports for tree removal other to providing access and egress.
  • To ensure your safety, do not drive or walk over downed power lines. Call you electricity company to report any faults.
  • Traffic Conditions are poor due to downed trees and traffic lights not working. Please drive to the conditions of the road and follow road rules where applicable/possible. In the event of unmanned intersections with inoperable traffic lights, come to a complete stop, proceed with caution at low speeds and at all time respecting other road users in the same position where no clear right of way exist.
Knox Residents
Support and Advice is available on Knox City Facebook and Knox City Web Site.

Monash Residents
Support and Advice is available on City of Monash Web Page

Greater Dandenong Residents
  • Visit Emergency Prepare Web Site for information on storms and power outages.
  • Greater Dandenong Libraries will be open to 9pm tonight offering residents the opportunity to charge mobile devices.
Casey Residents
  • A relief drop-in centre will be open tomorrow at 8am for residents who are currently without power at McNab Recreation Reserve, 8 Tony Way in Cranbourne West. Residents will have access to showers, power to charge their phones and other devices and phone reception.You must bring your own toiletries, towels and phone chargers.
  • Further information is available from City of Casey Web Site

Roads and Transport
  • For up to date information on road closures, visit VicRoads Traffic Web Site.

There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

Unless the situation changes, this will be the last message issued for this incident. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
